pageSummary: We are doing a (socially distanced) outdoor swim. because Of the support they offer to families in need.
pageSummaryWhat: We are doing a (socially distanced) outdoor swim.
pageSummaryWhy: Of the support they offer to families in need.
story:
On Saturday 16th January, Jane and Simone lost a dear friend to cancer. Simone's mother, and Eve's grandmother lost her life to this dreadful disease too. The Macmillan nurses played a vital part in making these passings as peaceful and supportive as possible. They are true angels in disguise. We are doing a socially distanced open water swim in the river warf on the 24th of January to raise money for Macmillan. We will be abiding by all Covid rules whilst swimming. If you would like to donate, please do so. Let's hope the water is not too cold! 

Thanks for supporting our fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you.Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Hey friends and family! Thanks SO MUCH for checking our my Just Giving page, you are all amazing 😄

I am running the 2021 Edinburgh Half Marathon for Macmillan Cancer Support in order to raise as much money as possible. No matter how much you are able to donate, I am super grateful for your support for Macmillan!

This period of time with Covid has been difficult for all of us, but those living with cancer deserve the best support possible and I am committed to raise money for them during this period of time. Let’s come together to raise a significant amount for an AMAZING charity!

No matter how many people are allowed to cheer the runners on during the race day, I’ll be training out there in the freezing Scottish weather to do my best to honour you guys who are giving so generously to Macmillan 🙌🏼

THANK YOU!

story: On the 10th July 2021 at 8am, a group of new and old runners and cyclists together to run in their own areas on the 10th July at 8am to raise money for Macmillan. Even more so awareness needs to be raised around Cancer and the affects it has on a lot of people. Sadly we all have our loses, but this is to honor them and help others. Individuals will complete a 15k run or 100k cycle and share their selfie and completion time. Please support us all. This is motivating during a mentally challenging time. story: Thank you for supporting my fundraising. I am carrying out this fundraiser in response to news that my mum has been diagnosed with cancer for the third time in multiple organs. There is nobody I know that is more selfless than my mum and this is why I am planning to give a little back that could potentially help her or others that are in the same situation. This is a charity that is very close to home and any donations would be amazing. I will be posting my progress whilst doing this fundraiser, thank you in advance.

eventName: Race to the Fulbeck for Dad - 400km in 74 days
pageSummary: Running to the Fulbeck pub, Mablethorpe (400km) because They looked after my Dad until he left us 💔
pageSummaryWhat: Running to the Fulbeck pub, Mablethorpe (400km)
pageSummaryWhy: They looked after my Dad until he left us 💔
story:
15 years ago my heart was broken along with my 6 brothers and sisters and my Mum and our lives were never the same again. I remember being at college getting a call from Mum and then in less than 2 weeks Dad was gone, no pre-warning, no time to digest what was happening and no time to make any more memories. 💔 

He was only 58 and loved by everyone that met him and had the funniest wittiest (dirtiest 🤦🏻‍♀️) sense pf humour! In all honestly he was a nightmare, loud, ex Army, but somehow he got away with it 🤷🏻‍♀️😂.  My son was only 1 years old and didn’t get a chance to get to know his Grandad but I’ve always been determined to keep his memory alive ❤️ 

Over the years I’ve done events such as an abseil and the Jurassic coast marathon but this year I thought I’d put my love of running to good use 🏃‍♀️ 

Dads favourite place to be was on holiday in Mablethorpe sat in the Fulbeck pub, drinking Brandy and peppermint, passing us £1 coins for the jukebox whilst we played pool...it’s definitely one of my happiest memories of us all as a family too so I’m going to run there! Obviously Covid is stopping me actually running there so instead I’ll run 400km (395.89km exactly from my house to the Fulbeck) in 74 days which is how old Dad would have been this year. 

All donations will be much appreciated and help so many families, I’d also love support from anyone that would like to run with me over the next 74 days ☺️ 

Thank you ❤️❤️

pageSummaryWhy: of the invaluable care and support they give.
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Diana Trimmer passed away peacefully on the 12th January 2021 at the age of 93. Wife of Peter and Mother of Trevor and 'big sister' to David and Laurie, Diana was also Grandmother to Jessica, Jack, Jaynie and Katie and Great Grandmother to Joshua. Long term resident of Four Marks in Hampshire, Diana played an especially important part in Jess’s life, after the sad loss of Trevor’s first wife Jenny.

Diana was a very kind and loving person who was always there to help others when they were having difficult times, including her family and friends and neighbours in Four Marks. She will be sadly missed by all those who looked to her for support when they needed someone to talk to.


Our love and thoughts go to Trevor, Lee, Jack, Jaynie, Katy, Jess, Andy and Joshua. Condolences and fond memories of Diana too from Pat, Jeremy, Ruth, Hannah, Matthew, Jo, Gareth and Mac and all of Diana’s relations in England, along with Australian cousins Julia, Josh, Josephine and Jonathan and their families.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: No chocolate, sweets or fizzy drink for March because Of heart disease ❤️❤️
pageSummaryWhat: No chocolate, sweets or fizzy drink for March
story:
My dad has been diagnosed with heart failure for some years now. It’s been a whole year since our lives were turned upside down and not everyone knows about this. I got the phone call I’ve dreaded...... it was my dad he had gone into cardiac arrest. For 30 minutes there was nothing and then his heart started beating again. He was rushed into hospital and I made the 3 hour journey down to be by his bedside as quick as I could. We began the rollercoaster journey I will never forget! 1 whole month in ICU, test after test, scans, you name it and the ‘worst’ kind of talks with the doctors but then the strongest man I know who I call my Dad came through it all and I’m so so so thankful to have him here with us today. This is thanks to all the amazing things that can be done to help people with heart disease, be able to continue their life. ❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️❤️

So I’m taking on this challenge so funds can be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. 

It’s a hard time for everyone at the moment, I know but I would be forever great full of you could just giving anything you can to this wonderful cause. 

Thank you in advance ❤️❤️

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: Doing this because I want to give back.
story:
I got diagnosed with heart failure in 2019 and ended up needing a heart transplant. Im lucky to be here today and I want to give back in anyway I can to help people that were in my situation a couple year back. I would appreciate all the help I can get. Also chocolate is my fav so its gonna be a tough month 😆

story:
So I am going to give it a go and cut out all chocolate, sweets and fizzy drinks throughout March 😄

COVID has caused us all to not go out, not see friends or eat out. So why not donate some of that money that you might have spent, to life saving research 🙌🏼 Even just £1 will help, every little helps and could make a huge difference.

Thankyou!

P.S wish me good luck 😟

story:

I then had a heart procedure at Kings College hospital in October 2020.  Please donate just £1 so that I can give something back to this worthy charity. ❤️❤️

I want to help as much as I can as they have been struggling with researching due to this pandemic. Please sponsor me and together we can fight heart disease 🙂

pageSummary: Giving up my essential food group Chocolate
pageSummaryWhat: Giving up my essential food group Chocolate
story:
One of my essential food groups is CHOCOLATE and I need it like I need water to survive.....or at least that's how it feels. .And so it will be a massive sacrifice to give it up, but give it up I will to help raise money for British Heart Foundation. A charity that is so close to my heart as it was heart failure that took my beloved dad. 

March is one of the years longest months and it was also the month of my dads birthday so it is fitting that I do this, this month, for my dad 

Giving up chocolate is going to be a major sacrifice but I will do it in honour of my dad, so please help make my sacrifice easier by knowing it's raising money

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
Great Ormond Street Hospital is the largest centre for child heart surgery in the UK and one of the largest centres for heart transplantation in the world.

Doctors and Nurses every day battle the most complex illnesses to give a better future for seriously ill children.

In April 1929 J.M. Barrie donated the copyright license of his Peter Pan works to the hospital.

Princess Diana served as president of the hospital from 1989 to the last day of her life.

story: Every day brings new challenges at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH). Every day, 618 children and young people from across the UK arrive. Every day, doctors and nurses battle the most complex illnesses, and the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs. And every day is a chance for you to make a difference. This extraordinary hospital has always depended on charitable support to give seriously ill children the best chance to fulfil their potential. A better future for seriously ill children STARTS HERE.

charity.description:
We are the world’s largest charity dedicated to saving lives through research.
Our vision is to bring forward the day when all cancers are cured.

Cancer Research UK is a registered charity in England and Wales (1089464), Scotland (SC041666), the Isle of Man (1103) and Jersey (247).
charity.name: Cancer Research UK
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 1089464, Scotland SC041666
eventName: Run 56 Miles in February for Cancer Research UK
story:
We are running 56 miles each in February to raise money for Cancer Research as donations have slowed down since Covid-19. 1 in 2 people get cancer in their lifetime.

Abbie: Before 2018 I had no idea on the impact that cancer has on individuals everyday. There is not a single day that goes by where I do not think about my Nanny Kath who lost her battle to ovarian cancer on 2nd November 2018. I am far from a runner, but I am doing this for her and others who have been affected by cancer. 

Georgia: After such a terrible year and now in our third lockdown I decided that I needed to continue with my lockdown hobby of walking and also continue my mission with being a confident runner. When Abbie sent me this challenge I thought what a perfect opportunity to give back and to remember those many people I know who have been affected by cancer especially as i lost two people very dear to heart, my lovely grandparents. 

No matter the time, no matter the weather, & no matter how tired we are, we will keep running and remember all those affected by cancer. 

With Abbie being a key worker and Georgia working, this is going to be a challenge especially with the long shifts, but we are determined! 

Please donate as much or as little as you can ✨

eventName: Cat's running 56 miles to raise money for Cancer Research UK
pageSummary: I am running 56 miles because I hate cancer!
story:
I'm raising money for Cancer Research UK and your contribution will make an impact, whether you donate a lot or a little.

We’ve all been touched by Cancer in some way. Many of us have lost parents, grandparents, aunts, uncles, siblings, and friends. I am, quite frankly sick of hearing the words, ‘I’ve got cancer’. I’ve heard them recently from my friends, Jinx, Amie, Tina, Nicki, and my aunt Lynney. Lynney and Jinx are still fighting, but I’m delighted to say that my other friends are in good health.

My friend Rachael Sargeant was diagnosed with Breast Cancer in September. I cannot even begin to imagine what that must have felt like. Rachael and I were good friends at school, and she has a young son, Oliver.

The good news is that the prognosis is good, it’s been caught early and is treatable. She sought medical assistance as soon as she found a lump.

The ‘not so good news’ (in the words of her surgeon) is that the histology results show that her tumour, which they initially thought was non-invasive, did contain an invasive mass within it. This wasn’t expected. Fortunately, it hadn’t spread as was caught early. Further testing has been done to see what receptors it contained - as most breast cancers will grow from 3 of them, meaning hormone therapies can be used to stop reoccurrence. In a small % none of these are present so a diagnosis of ‘triple negative breast cancer’ is given and no hormone therapies etc can be used to prevent reoccurrence.

You’ve guessed it, that’s what hers is.

She needs Chemotherapy and Radiotherapy, and yearly mammograms until she is 50. She needs to shield for 12 weeks meaning that she has to be incredibly careful about who she mixes with, at a time when she needs all the support she can get.

Rachael has been through surgery, and is now going through Chemo, in the middle of a pandemic.
Let that sink in for a moment. In the middle of a pandemic. Cancer is hard. Rachael has only just turned 40.

I can’t do much to help Rachael at the moment, but I can help raise money for the amazing charity that has so much amazing work and has got us to the point where Cancer IS treatable. I will therefore be running 56 miles during the month of February for your hard-earned cash!

If you can spare just a few pounds I would be so grateful.

Together we will beat cancer.

Facebook pays all the processing fees for you, so 100% of your donation goes directly to the non-profit.Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
Our lovely Dad sadly passed away very suddenly and far too soon on 5th January 2021.  He had battled various illnesses the previous year but bravely soldiered on.  He was finally taken by this dreadful virus, COVID -19, and unfortunately this same virus is stopping many of you from being with us at his funeral. Dad would not have wished it to be this way.

Dad did leave some directions for his funeral and it is his expression of wish that instead of floral tributes, should people wish to do so, they are able to contribute to this very worthy and valuable cause.

He thought very highly of each and every one of you and wish you all well.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
We've been caring for people with serious illnesses in Barnet, Brent, Camden, Enfield, Haringey and Islington for more than 60 years, now.

Every single day at the hospice is an extraordinary day. And every moment is precious. Our hospice nurses, doctors and therapists provide the best possible care for people with serious illnesses, and offer vital emotional support for them and their families. 

The hospice is a warm, welcoming place where loved ones can be together in peaceful surroundings and in as much comfort as possible. Whether it's for one day or several weeks, the time people spend at the hospice is precious, and is cherished by them and their families.

Thank you for supporting us, and helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in North London get the care and support they need.

"When I was admitted, I was confined to a wheelchair, in constant pain. Now I walk between five and seven miles a day. You can see how good Marie Curie is in that I walk" - Matthew

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

Their nurses are absolute stars and I can't thank them enough for all that they did. Please help me raise money for a cause which is very close to my and my family's hearts. Thankyou

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

pageSummary: Sampson is going to run, bike or walk 62km in Jan because he’d like to help the charity save lives at sea.
pageSummaryWhat: Sampson is going to run, bike or walk 62km in Jan
pageSummaryWhy: he’d like to help the charity save lives at sea.
story:
Sampson is 11 years old and is missing his year 7 friends and playing sport at his favourite clubs. He has decided to use lockdown January to do something positive, raising money for a good cause, and has set himself the target of 2km every single day in Jan, running, walking or biking. He’d like to raise £62, £1 for every km.

Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. pageSummaryWhy: I love animals and want to help save our planet
story:
Sophie has been learning how to use her skipping rope to keep fit and use her energy during lockdown. She decided she'd like to raise some money for charity so together we came up with the idea of her completing 800 skips in no more than 8 days from her 8th birthday (which is 28th Jan). Sophie can skip on the spot or skip around the garden but only a complete loop with the skipping rope counts. Mummy will be checking!

Sophie is very interested in animals and is learning about how many beautiful creatures are endangered. She would like to do more to help, so has chosen to donate to WWF.

About WWF

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Hi, I'm Ella and I'm 13 years old. I have hand-sewn a lovely set of felt decorations for Easter because I want to raise money for the WWF. 

Every penny donated will go directly to the WWF and I will choose a donor at random to get the prize which is the Easter set in the photo. The set includes : 3 sheep decorations, 3 egg decorations, a 3 piece sheep hanging decoration and a sheep card. 4 other donors will also be picked at random too and the 4 prizes are : A panda keyring, a large panda circle, a small panda circle and a walrus keyring. I chose the panda because they are endangered and the logo for the WWF and I chose the walrus because they are endangered too and after watching David Attenborough's 'Our Planet', I knew that they needed our help, just like lots of other species like the snow leopard and the mountain gorilla and sadly, increasingly more but we can do something about it if we change our ways.

The reason why I am raising money for the WWF is because of David Attenborough as he has inspired me to do something about climate change. I had always cared about the environment but I was shocked when I found out about how much damage was actually caused because of humans. 

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world's most important challenges: protecting endangered species, safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature can thrive. Your support is much appreciated. Find out more on how we can protect the world by visiting wwf.org.uk.

Please make sure that if you want to try and get a prize, you need to put your full name and correct email address so I can easily contact you.  

Please don't forget to share this post so we can tackle climate change together.

Thank you,

Ella

story: We're doing a virtue journey 20,000km from St Albans (UK) to Cox's Bazar (Bangladesh), visiting Oxfam projects along the way. We'll see the challenges communities face from conflict, to Covid-19 to the impact of the climate emergency and how Oxfam is responding to support communities to thrive, not just survive. With your support, Oxfam can continue its life-saving work, it can continue to put together packages of food, give farming support, set up foodbanks, support education for women and girls, and provide cash to buy essentials. For each £15 we raise, we could help more women to understand their rights, challenge discrimination and to take up leadership roles within their local communities. For each £35, we could help families access emergency food supplies. £45 could provide one of our new handwashing stations to enable frequent handwashing and disease prevention. With your support, communities can come together to help each other.

story:
Climate change is affecting millions of the worlds poorest people, right now. More frequent and extreme weather is destroying homes, and wrecking lives. The people who have done the least to cause the climate emergency are being hit the hardest this is an injustice that can and must be stopped.

Oxfam is protecting families forced to flee their homes, supporting those hit by changing weather, making sure children have a chance of a future free from poverty and responding to the deadly threat of coronavirus. Through all of this, we rely on brilliant supporters like you to make sure our dedicated teams can be where they're needed most. We couldn't do our work without you.

Every donation, no matter how big or small, makes a difference. 

Together, we won't live with poverty.

story: I am fundraising because Unicef urgently need funds to expand the scale and scope of their work supporting children affected by coronavirus, especially in countries with weaker health systems. Just £30 could provide a full kit to protect a health-worker on the frontline, including gloves, masks and coveralls, while just £43 could help provide 1,680 pairs of disposable gloves for health workers. The impact of a large-scale outbreak of coronavirus on children, especially poor and vulnerable children, has been immense. Children are at risk from the disease, but also from the disruption to health and education services, impacts on caregivers, and separation from family members. Unicef has been working closely with governments and the World Health Organization (WHO) since the start of the coronavirus outbreak. Donations made to my page will help to limit the spread of the virus and reduce the impact on children and families.

story: Throughout the globe Covid-19 has spread rapidly. Although UK has seen its own share of illness and death we are very lucky enough to have first class healthcare service and government support in this crisis. Unfortunately others around the world are not so lucky. In an attempt to give back to those in need this February Isaac Guppy, Cam Graetz, Max Waldron and Julian Hannah have set themselves a challenge to run 300km each throughout the month (averaging 10km a day) in order to raise money for UNICEF. UNICEF, also known as the united nations children’s fund, is a United Nations agency responsible for providing humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide. We extend the invitation to anyone who would like to join us on our ‘Rona Run’ or set your own challenge for the month and help support those in need!

story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. 

Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in climate-vulnerable communities.
